SIMPLE: spike
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spike
<hw>Spike</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to LG.
<ets>spiker</ets>, <ets>spieker</ets>, a large nail, D.
<ets>spijker</ets>, Sw. <ets>spik</ets>, Dan. <ets>spiger</ets>, Icel.
<ets>sp⟦imac⟧k</ets>; all perhaps from L. <ets>spica</ets> a point, an
ear of grain; but in the sense of nail more likely akin to E.
<ets>spoke</ets> of a wheel. Cf. <er>Spine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A sort of very large nail; also, a piece of pointed iron set with
points upward or outward.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything resembling such a nail in shape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wears on his head the <qex>corona radiata</qex> . . . ; the
<qex>spikes</qex> that shoot out represent the rays of the sun.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An ear of corn or grain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of flower cluster in which
sessile flowers are arranged on an unbranched elongated axis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Spike grass</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>either of
two tall perennial American grasses (<spn>Uniola paniculata</spn>, and
<spn>Uniola latifolia</spn>) having broad leaves and large flattened
spikelets.</cd> -- <col><b>Spike rush</b></col>. <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<cd>See under <er>Rush</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spike shell</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any pteropod of the genus <gen>Styliola</gen>
having a slender conical shell.</cd> -- <col><b>Spike team</b></col>,
<cd>three horses, or a horse and a yoke of oxen, harnessed together, a
horse leading the oxen or the span.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spike</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spike
<hw>Spike</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spiked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spiking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fasten with
spikes, or long, large nails; <as>as, to <ex>spike</ex> down
planks</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set or furnish with spikes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fix on a spike.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Young.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To stop the vent of (a gun or cannon) by driving a
spike nail, or the like into it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- (Sport) To throw violently to the ground, so that it bounces.
Sometimes done by football players after scoring a goal, as a victory
celebration. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spike</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spike
<hw>Spike</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. G. <ets>spieke</ets>, L.
<ets>spica</ets> an ear of grain. See <er>Spikenard</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Spike lavender. See <er>Lavender</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Oil of spike</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>a
colorless or yellowish aromatic oil extracted from the European
broad-leaved lavender, or aspic (<spn>Lavendula Spica</spn>), used in
artist's varnish and in veterinary medicine. It is often adulterated
with oil of turpentine, which it much resembles.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spikebill</ent>⟦br⟧
